From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v15 - require MSI/MSI-X for PS4 Liverpool IRQs

Port of rmuxnet c0066db41 to our 6.15.4 amdgpu_irq.c.  The original
patch had context drift (rmuxnet's tree is on a different kernel
version), so this is the same logical change, hand-adapted to our
exact source.

Why: PS4 has NO ACPI _PRT entries describing INTx routing for the
GPU at 0000:00:01.0.  amdgpu's default behavior (try MSI, fall back
to INTx if MSI fails) ends up with INTx → "can't find IRQ for PCI
INT A; please try using pci=biosirq" → no IRQ → all command-
completion polls time out → endless GPU resets → "asic atom init
failed".

Fix: for CHIP_LIVERPOOL and CHIP_GLADIUS ASICs, require MSI/MSI-X
explicitly (PCI_IRQ_MSI | PCI_IRQ_MSIX, no INTx).  If MSI alloc
fails, return error rather than silently falling back to INTx.

Expected effect:
- amdgpu gets a real LAPIC vector
- IRQ delivery to amdgpu_irq_handler works
- GPU command completion notifications arrive
- Ring submissions complete instead of timing out
- "Illegal instruction in command stream" errors stop (these were
  caused by the GPU's CP retrying state-init commands after timeout
  with stale ring state)

Reference:
  rmuxnet c0066db41 ("amdgpu: require MSI/MSI-X for PS4 Liverpool IRQs")
  research/rmuxnet-12xx-current/
---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_irq.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/amdgpu_irq.c
@@ -257,6 +257,17 @@
 	pci_write_config_word(adev->pdev, adev->pdev->msix_cap + PCI_MSIX_FLAGS, ctrl);
 }
 
+
+/* v15 (rmuxnet c0066db41): PS4 Liverpool/Gladius have no INTx routing,
+ * so amdgpu MUST use MSI/MSI-X.  Without this, amdgpu probe falls back
+ * to INTx, fails to find an IRQ ("can't find IRQ for PCI INT A"), and
+ * every command-completion poll times out → endless GPU resets. */
+static bool amdgpu_irq_is_ps4_asic(struct amdgpu_device *adev)
+{
+	return adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL ||
+	       adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS;
+}
+
 /**
  * amdgpu_irq_init - initialize interrupt handling
  *
@@ -271,6 +282,7 @@
 int amdgpu_irq_init(struct amdgpu_device *adev)
 {
 	unsigned int irq, flags;
+	bool ps4_asic = amdgpu_irq_is_ps4_asic(adev);
 	int r;
 
 	spin_lock_init(&adev->irq.lock);
@@ -278,19 +290,37 @@
 	/* Enable MSI if not disabled by module parameter */
 	adev->irq.msi_enabled = false;
 
-	if (!amdgpu_msi_ok(adev))
+	if (ps4_asic) {
+		if (!amdgpu_msi_ok(adev)) {
+			dev_err(adev->dev,
+				"PS4: INTx is not supported for Liverpool/Gladius; MSI/MSI-X required\n");
+			return -EINVAL;
+		}
+		flags = PCI_IRQ_MSI | PCI_IRQ_MSIX;
+	} else if (!amdgpu_msi_ok(adev)) {
 		flags = PCI_IRQ_INTX;
-	else
+	} else {
 		flags = PCI_IRQ_ALL_TYPES;
+	}
 
 	/* we only need one vector */
+	dev_dbg(adev->dev, "irq allocation flags=0x%x\n", flags);
 	r = pci_alloc_irq_vectors(adev->pdev, 1, 1, flags);
 	if (r < 0) {
 		dev_err(adev->dev, "Failed to alloc msi vectors\n");
 		return r;
 	}
 
-	if (amdgpu_msi_ok(adev)) {
+	if (ps4_asic) {
+		adev->irq.msi_enabled = pci_dev_msi_enabled(adev->pdev);
+		if (!adev->irq.msi_enabled) {
+			dev_err(adev->dev,
+				"PS4: INTx is not supported for Liverpool/Gladius; MSI/MSI-X required\n");
+			pci_free_irq_vectors(adev->pdev);
+			return -ENODEV;
+		}
+		dev_dbg(adev->dev, "using MSI/MSI-X.\n");
+	} else if (amdgpu_msi_ok(adev)) {
 		adev->irq.msi_enabled = true;
 		dev_dbg(adev->dev, "using MSI/MSI-X.\n");
 	}
